Cosmon keeps a fleet of AI agents on track. Run several on one codebase and a session will crash, or fill its context window and forget what it was doing, and you lose track of which agent was on what — cosmon gives each a durable identity and writes every step to disk, so a dead session resumes where it stopped and you can always see who is doing what. More generally it runs missions you delegate to AI: it breaks a hard problem into typed, ordered steps, executes them, and records every step so the finished work carries an auditable trace — the reasoning matters as much as the result. Nothing in it is code-specific; it aims just as well at research-grade missions, where a technical lock demands long, decomposed, checkable work. It is model-agnostic, sitting above any model, so your context and data stay with you and a mission can run entirely on local models. Cosmon is the kernel of noogram — the open-source substrate for composing, piloting and auditing missions entrusted to AI systems.

PILOT WORKFLOW — the full cycle is nucleate → tackle → wait → done:
  cs nucleate <formula> ...       create molecule
  cs tackle <id>                  spawn ONE worker on this node — always
                                  leaf, never walks the DAG. The verb is
                                  picked by the operator: cs tackle = single
                                  node; cs run = N≥1 nodes (resident runtime).
  cs wait <id> &                  background wait, get notified on completion
  cs done <id>                    merge branch to main + teardown (required!)

Pilots NEVER poll 'cs observe' by hand — always use 'cs wait'. Pilots NEVER skip 'cs done' — without it the branch never merges. Pilots NEVER run 'cs run' in the foreground — wrap it in a detached tmux session: tmux new -d -s runtime cs run <root> --poll-interval 5 (cs run calls cs done automatically on completion). The historical '--leaf' and '--force-runtime' flags on 'cs tackle' are deprecated no-ops since the verb-unification: pick the right verb instead.

ANTI-PREEMPTION LEASE. A human 'cs tackle' and a running 'cs run' are two writers racing on the same Pending → Active flip, so every tackle records WHO dispatched it: 'cs tackle --by human' (the default) or 'cs tackle --by runtime:<pid>' (what 'cs run' passes). The walker re-reads each candidate fresh from disk right before dispatch and SKIPS anything no longer Pending, carrying a sticky 'human' claim, or tagged 'hold:pilot'. Use 'cs claim <id>' before reaching for a pending molecule: it writes the durable pilot hold before 'cs tackle', and 'cs release <id>' removes it. The runtime always defers to that hold. 'manual always wins', the runtime never raffles a molecule you reached for. Binary owner field, no clock to calibrate. Operators do not normally type '--by'; 'human' is the default.

SPORE (ADR-140) germinates a whole polymer from a shareable 'spore.toml' template, the way 'cs nucleate' germinates one molecule. A spore is a parameterizable mission plan: a fleet, per-node formulas, a ParamSchema, a DAG of typed edges, and an optional '.tla' seal. Three verbs, one role each:
  cs spore validate <ref>         parse + expand as a dry run; prints
                                  the ordered nucleate call list,
                                  germinates nothing.
  cs spore run <ref>              parse + expand + seal gate, then
                                  germinate the polymer into the live
                                  state store (every node tagged
                                  temp:warm, wired to its blocked-by).
  cs spore export <ref>           content-addressed bundle hash +
                                  ASTRA descriptive layer (D6).

'<ref>' is a 'spore.toml' file or a directory containing one. '--var k=v' (repeatable) binds a parameter, coerced into its declared ParamSchema type before expansion. '--json' on validate and run emits NDJSON (agent-first invariant). A spore is a declarative front end over the existing 'cs nucleate' verb, not a new scheduler and not a new molecule type.

SEAL GATE (ADR-140 D4), stated honestly: a spore with no [spore.seal] germinates freely ('seal: none'). A sealed spore cannot be proven on a machine without the TLC verifier wired in, so 'cs spore run' fails closed by default and refuses unless the operator opts into the risk with '--allow-unchecked-seal', in which case the status line reads 'seal: present, NOT verified'. It never claims 'verified' when TLC did not run. See docs/cs-spore.md and docs/design/spore-impl-dag-manifest.md.

MONITORING — the operator's toolkit (use these, not tmux/tail/cat):
  cs peek                         watchdog TUI — every unfinished molecule
                                  (running, pending, frozen, starved; the
                                   archive is hidden by default; press A
                                   to cycle or pass --phase)
  cs peek --phase done,failed     + the archive (completed + collapsed)
  cs peek --all-galaxies          same phases, every project
  cs peek --all                   sugar for --all-galaxies --phase all:
                                  everything, every project, archive
                                  included (multi-galaxy)
  cs peek --snapshot              byte-deterministic 120-col canonical view
                                  (same bytes on any device; cf.
                                   docs/guides/peek-snapshot.md)
  cs peek --json                  machine view: one JSON document,
                                  printed once, sorted by molecule id
  cs ensemble --tag temp:hot      actionable backlog snapshot
  cs wait <id> &                  block on a worker without hanging the pilot

Observability is a fractal portal, not a dashboard: one tool (cs peek), recursive, from fleet overview down to per-molecule artifact. Reach for 'cs peek' before 'tmux attach', 'tail -f', or 'cat briefing.md'.

cs peek navigates three continuous scales via zoom keys: '+' steps in (ville → immeuble → peau), '-' steps out, '=' resets to ville. Ville is the fleet table; immeuble is one molecule pleine-page with adjacent neighbours wired by straight monospace DAG cables; peau is the raw artifact (briefing / synthesis / log / …) at full resolution. See docs/guides/peek-zoom.md.

cs peek --json — the machine projection. One JSON document, printed once: {"filter", "molecules": [{"id", "project", "status", "heartbeat", "last_activity", "updated_at"}]}, sorted by id so two captures of an unchanged fleet diff to nothing. 'status' is the raw core status — the same word 'cs observe --json' reports for the same molecule, never re-lettered, and an unrecognised future status serialises as its own snake_case name rather than being laundered into 'pending'. 'heartbeat' is the liveness tier (active|idle|quiet|stalled|orphaned); 'last_activity' is the timestamp it was classified from, but it folds in tmux's attach-bumped session clock, so merely attaching moves it — 'updated_at' moves only on a state write and is what a stall or orphan patrol should read. 'filter' names the published slice, so absence is distinguishable from filtered-by-design. 'project' is a display label, not a join key. '--phase'/'--all' select the same molecules as on screen; '--json' wins over '--snapshot'. No bucket field: that taxonomy is under active redesign, and publishing it would freeze a machine contract to the one object with a demonstrated re-cut cadence. Token counts live in 'cs ensemble --json'.

cs peek also drives the fleet from inside the TUI. Cockpit action keystrokes open a thin modal that fires one 'cs <verb>' and waits: 'n' nucleate (formula + topic), 't' tackle the selected row, 'm' merge-and-done (cs done) with y/N confirmation, 'w' whisper a body to the selected worker, '.' append a session note. Esc cancels any modal. Detail-pane letters 'n' and 't' moved to 'N' (notes) and 'T' (tree); the mouse-capture toggle moved from 'm' to 'M'.

cs peek — presence header strip. When '.cosmon/state/presence/*.json' files exist, a one-line strip under the title lists every live Claude session (galaxy "headline"). Stale entries (heartbeat > 3 min) render greyed; files without a heartbeat are dropped. The strip is a read-only wheat-paste over the presence registry owned by C-PRESENCE-CORE ('cs presence ping|ls|gc').

cs peek — ensemble tab ('E' key). Hot-swaps the molecule table for a fleet-wide events view, newest-first. Columns: ts | mol_id | kind | summary. 'j/k' scrolls; Enter closes the tab and zooms on the selected molecule. Useful above N≈50 live molecules when the per-row detail panes drown the signal.

cs peek — non-interactive filter flags: '--filter <str>' pre-populates the TUI '/' field; '--tag <t>' restricts to molecules carrying that tag; '--since <ts|dur>' hides rows older than an RFC-3339 timestamp or a duration suffix ('30m', '2h', '3d'); '--since-event N' keeps only the last N events per molecule in the ensemble view. Together they keep cs peek readable at large N.

cs peek — phases. Every molecule sits in exactly one phase, and the phase is a total function of its status: 'live' (running), 'waiting' (pending + queued), 'blocked' (starved — an external authority refused service, ADR-062), 'parked' (frozen), 'failed' (collapsed) and 'done' (completed). The TUI table and the '--no-tui' baseline both default to the unfinished ones — every phase that is not 'failed' or 'done'. The archive is what drowns the daily signal; the frozen, starved and pending rows are the signal, and no other instrument reports them. One flag per axis widens the slice: '--phase' selects the phases ('--phase done,failed' adds the archive), '--all-galaxies' selects the projects, and neither touches the other's axis. '--all' is sugar for '--all-galaxies --phase all' and is the only flag that speaks to both. The interactive 'A' key cycles the phase filter (unfinished → all → unfinished) with a status-line label; the lowercase 'a' key still toggles the all-projects scope independently. Live transition events (status change, step advance, worker reassignment) are always shown in '--no-tui' mode regardless of the filter — they are the signal the operator subscribed to. See docs/guides/peek-temporalities.md.

REGISTERING A SERVICE — two métiers, two tools:
  cosmon-scheduler (patrols.toml)   the house's alarm clock. Periodic,
                                    short-lived gestures — cron/interval fires.
                                    Example: executor-pulse every 2h, chronicle-
                                    lint Sunday 09:00, WhatsApp sync every 15min.
  cosmon-daemon-supervisor          the night watchman. Long-running
                                    (daemons.toml)                    processes that must stay alive —
                                    Telegram bot, Emacs daemon, MCP servers.

Decision rule — does the command finish on its own?
  Yes, re-fire on a cadence               -> cosmon-scheduler
  No, runs forever, restart if it dies    -> cosmon-daemon-supervisor

Operator views: cs scheduler status / cs daemons list|status|logs|reload.
Shared kill-switch: 'touch ~/.cosmon/stand-down.lock' silences both.

SCHEDULER DRY-RUN OUTPUT — four row types, one per patrol:
  FIRE     patrol is due; dispatch would spawn the command now
  SKIP     gate rejected (disabled, kill-switch, not-due-yet,
           already-sunsetted, missing require_env var, …)
  SUNSET   a [patrol.sunset] convergence rule fired. Scheduler
           records sunset_decided_at, emits patrol.sunsetted, runs
           on_sunset hooks, then short-circuits to SKIP on every
           subsequent tick.
  INVALID  schema or cadence error (cron parse failure, cadence
           XOR violation). Exit code 3.

Auto-sunset for probes: attach [patrol.sunset] to stop a measurement campaign on a statistical criterion (variance-threshold / sample-count / operator-trigger-only) instead of a calendar timer. TSV shape and hook flags (notify_telegram, write_chronicle_stub) are described in docs/probes/sample-file-convention.md.
Canonical image: the chronicle 2026-04-19 'Deux métiers, deux outils' (réveil vs. veilleur de nuit) and 2026-04-19 'Le gardien des chiens, et le gardien des portes' (the supervisor-of-the-supervisor is launchd — one plist for the watchman, N dogs under its care).
Future: dynamic service registration (today both layers are TOML-
edited; a planned design will let a service register itself via 
event/API/molecule — see the internal design notes for the design space).

ARCHIVE — durable proof-of-work trail (ADR-030, see docs/archive.md):
  cs archive list                 every archived molecule, all months
  cs archive list --year 2026     scoped to one year
  cs archive show <mol>           manifest + artifact inventory (prefix ok)
  cs archive verify <mol>         recompute SHA-256 hashes (exit 1 if tampered)
  cs archive prune --dry-run      what [archive.retention] would delete
  cs archive prune                execute the retention policy

Terminal transitions (cs done / cs collapse / cs freeze / cs stuck) populate '.cosmon/state/archive/YYYY/MM/<id>/' when [archive] enabled = true in the project config. The archive outlives worktree teardown — a fresh clone sees every merged molecule's canonical snapshot without running cs.

Worked example — verify the current month's archive in CI:
  cs archive list --year "$(date +%Y)" --month "$(date +%m)" --json \
    | jq -r '.entries[].molecule_id' \
    | xargs -I{} cs archive verify {}

LOOPS — three places an agent loop can live (chronicle 2026-05-19 'Trois places, un nom différé'):
  L-Ext         outside cosmon. The loop runs in an external binary cosmon spawns through a tmux pane;
                cosmon owns spawn / supervision / pane-signature / liveness, nothing of the loop itself.
                Adapters today: claude, aider, codex, opencode. SupervisionMode = TmuxPane, LoopOwnership = External.
  L-Native      inside cosmon. The loop runs in-process inside 'cs tackle' (cosmon-provider +
                cosmon-agent-harness); cosmon owns the FSM, tool dispatch, message log, briefing seal.
                Adapters today: openai, anthropic, llama-cpp (with 'llama' as legacy CLI alias).
                SupervisionMode = InProcess, LoopOwnership = Cosmon.
  L-Composite   above cosmon. N typed roles share a typed state (RoleRoutingTable). Vocabulary, not a
                Rust enum yet — a meta-deliberation refused the three-variant enum because
                Composite is set-level (a property of an aggregate) while External and Cosmon are atom-level
                (a property per Adapter). Lives today in academy's meta-fleet, barely instantiated cosmon-side.

A second axis, RuntimeOwnership, names *who runs the model server* the loop talks to (ADR-104). It is orthogonal to LoopOwnership: a Cosmon loop can talk to a Vendor server (openai, anthropic via the Direct-API path) or to an Operated server (llama-cpp in-process, vllm-mlx sidecar). The 2×2 grid:
  (Cosmon, Operated)    cosmon runs the loop, the operator can pull the model-server's plug.
                          llama-cpp today (in-process FFI), vllm-mlx tomorrow (Path B sidecar).
  (Cosmon, Vendor)      cosmon runs the loop, the model server is a vendor cosmon merely consumes.
                          openai, anthropic today (Direct-API).
  (External, Vendor)    cosmon spawns an external CLI talking to its vendor cloud.
                          claude, aider, codex, opencode today (tmux-pane subprocess).
  (External, Operated)  reserved — no shipped row yet (e.g. self-hosted Codex driven by cosmon).

Per-Adapter axes are read from BUILT_IN_AXES at crates/cosmon-core/src/spawn_seam.rs and validated at every 'cs tackle'. ADRs: ADR-099 (ValidatedAdapterName), ADR-101 (SupervisionMode), ADR-103 (LoopOwnership), ADR-104 (RuntimeOwnership).

ADAPTERS — canonical names and their per-Adapter axes (registry projection, ADR-106 D2/D4):
  claude        (TmuxPane,  External, Vendor)    Claude Code CLI in a tmux pane — vendor cloud.
  aider         (TmuxPane,  External, Vendor)    aider CLI in a tmux pane — non-LLM coding agent.
  codex         (TmuxPane,  External, Vendor)    OpenAI Codex CLI in a tmux pane — vendor cloud. Interactive steerable TUI by default (whisperable, parity with claude); [adapters.codex].mode = "exec" for the legacy fire-and-forget 'codex exec' batch path.
  opencode      (TmuxPane,  External, Vendor)    opencode (sst/opencode) CLI in a tmux pane — vendor cloud.
  openai        (InProcess, Cosmon,   Vendor)    OpenAI chat-completions HTTP, in-process loop (cosmon-agent-harness).
  anthropic     (InProcess, Cosmon,   Vendor)    Anthropic messages HTTP, in-process loop (cosmon-agent-harness).
  llama-cpp     (InProcess, Cosmon,   Operated)  llama.cpp FFI in-process — operator-run weights on operator hardware.
  llama         (InProcess, Cosmon,   Operated)  legacy CLI alias of llama-cpp (ADR-106 D4) — emits the canonical name in events.
  local         (InProcess, Cosmon,   Operated)  Ollama OpenAI-compat /v1 in-process loop — the built-in default, no Claude Code.
  ollama        (InProcess, Cosmon,   Operated)  canonical alias of 'local' (task-20260707-7d27) — '--adapter ollama' routes to the same floor and stamps 'ollama' in events.

Selection happens at 'cs tackle' time. Resolution order:
  'cs tackle --adapter <NAME>'      → CLI flag wins.
  formula step 'adapter = "<NAME>"'  → per-workflow override (e.g. a deep-think panel pins claude).
  $COSMON_DEFAULT_ADAPTER            → operator session hammer (one export, everywhere, no committed config).
  '.cosmon/config.toml::[adapters.default]'  → per-galaxy default for the project.
  '~/.config/cosmon/config.toml::[adapters.default]'  → global machine-wide default (only when the per-galaxy config is silent).
  built-in 'local'                  → config-undeletable floor (Ollama-backed, no Claude Code in the default path).

Every 'cs tackle' invocation — with or without the flag — emits one 'adapter_selected' envelope to events.jsonl carrying { adapter_name, selection_source (cli|formula_step|env_var|config|global_config|default), role_hint?, loop_ownership (cosmon|external) }. The cat-test over the event log answers "which Adapter ran for this molecule?" without parsing shell history (jq -c 'select(.type == "adapter_selected")'). The same envelope is what 'cs demo' will reuse when its --adapter pass-through lands — the demo verb merely forwards the flag to 'cs tackle'; the dispatch site is unchanged.

Discovery path: an unknown name on 'cs tackle --adapter <UNKNOWN>' aborts with a typed 'AdapterNotFound' carrying the available names — no silent fallback (godin's error-path discoverability rule). The full registry projection is exposed read-only via 'cs config adapters [--json]' (cs.adapters.list/v1 envelope, ADR-106 D3).

Loud fallback: a local model hard-failure (crash/oom/timeout/connection-refused) reaches a remote oracle ONLY via 'cs tackle --adapter <REMOTE> --fallback-from-local <CAUSE>'. That re-tackle mints a 'local_fallback' line in the same atom as the 'remote_egress_opt_in' egress grant, so a fallback can never be silent. There is no automatic in-loop fallback; soft 'is the output good?' judgement is undecidable (Rice) and is not a valid cause.

MODEL SELECTION (per-molecule, ADR-097). A model pin is the sibling of the adapter axis, resolved fresh at every 'cs tackle' — strong is NEVER inherited, silence resolves cheap. Resolution order:
  'cs tackle --model <ID>'          → CLI flag wins.
  formula step 'model = "<ID>"'     → per-workflow pin (does NOT propagate across nucleation).
  $COSMON_DEFAULT_MODEL (else legacy $ANTHROPIC_MODEL)  → operator session hammer.
  '.cosmon/config.toml::[adapters.<name>.default_model]'  → per-galaxy default, SCOPED to the adapter.
  '~/.config/cosmon/config.toml::[adapters.<name>.default_model]'  → global default (only when the per-galaxy config is silent).
  floor 'None'                      → cosmon pins NO model; the adapter's own default applies (byte-identical to no pin — a strong model is unreachable from silence).

The id is carried opaquely: cosmon does not validate that <ID> is legal for the adapter — the backend rejects an invalid (adapter, model) pair at launch (composition validation is C5). The claude adapter carries the pin through the ANTHROPIC_MODEL per-session closure-shadow at spawn (no shared-state mutation); the Direct-API adapters take it above their config default_model.

MODEL BUDGET (fail-closed strong-dispatch ceiling, ADR-097). Declare which ids are STRONG (expensive) per adapter and cap strong dispatches per window — both opt-in:
  '[adapters.<name>].strong = ["<id>", ...]'  → the strong cost-class set. FAIL-OPEN: an unlisted id is non-strong (cheap); a cost-class annotation, NOT a validity table.
  '[model_budget] strong_dispatch_cap = <K>'  → at most K strong dispatches per 'window_hours' (default 24); absent ⇒ no ceiling. 'on_overflow' = "downgrade" (default — drop to the safe floor) or "abort" (refuse).
  The count is a fold over 'events.jsonl' (never a counter file); the (K+1)th strong pin fails closed and mints a 'model_ceiling_hit' event. SAFE-DEFAULT GUARD: strong is reachable ONLY from --model / a formula-pin; a strong config/env default is dropped to the floor, and a strong '[adapters.<name>].default_model' FAILS 'cs reconcile --check' (config may only downgrade).

Name stability: 'llama-cpp' is the canonical CLI name for the in-process llama.cpp FFI adapter; 'llama' is a legacy alias kept at the CLI seam only (ADR-106 D4) — the persisted ProviderId serialises as 'llama_cpp' with serde(alias = "llama"), and AdapterSelected emits the canonical name even when the operator typed the alias. The KebabRenameBait set { openai, llama } is tolerated at input but excluded from the published ProtocolStableNames list the TLA+ invariant I3 RegistryTruth reads (docs/specs/CosmonDocHarness.tla).

Usage: cs [OPTIONS] <COMMAND>

Commands:
  ensemble        Display ensemble status — observe the fleet at a glance
  nucleate        Nucleate a new molecule from a formula template
  observe         Observe a molecule's current state and history
  errors          Errors — aggregate molecule-collapse events into one failure overview: what is breaking the fleet, and which molecules are hit
  evolve          Evolve a molecule to its next lifecycle state
  collapse        Collapse a molecule — terminate with final state recording
  complete        Complete a molecule — idempotent Active→Completed transition (worker-callable)
  decay           Decay a molecule into child molecules (1 → N)
  merge           Merge molecules into a synthesis (N → 1)
  transform       Transform a molecule's kind (idea → task, etc.)
  init            Bootstrap a project-local .cosmon/ directory (creates the target dir if missing)
  inbox           Inbox — vertical pile of atomic actions awaiting operator decision (cs inbox)
  spark           Spark — capture a one-line operator intent into the Inbox (ADR-061)
  drop            Drop — universal Inbox gesture (hotkey / zsh widget / menubar) → `cs spark`
  listen          Listen — voice → whisper.cpp → `cs nucleate spark` (MVP)
  pilot           Pilot — interactive cognitive pilot REPL over a client-side model (--experimental). --remote pilots an avatar over the §8p wire (ADR-115)
  kill            Kill a worker — immediate termination (no state flush)
  quench          Quench a worker — graceful shutdown with state preservation
  fleet           Fleet template discovery and initialization
  galaxies        Galaxies — inspect the four-family taxonomy
  freeze          Freeze a worker — suspend with state preservation (preemption)
  thaw            Thaw a worker — resume a frozen worker's Claude session
  trust           Trust — grant this repository permission to run its own formulas/hooks (the `direnv allow` of cosmon; refuses repo-supplied shell until granted)
  prime           Prime the system — load .cosmon/config.toml and self-check gates
  resume          Resume — convenience alias for `cs patrol --propel --molecule <id>`
  teardown        Teardown a fleet — gracefully stop all fleet workers
  purge           Purge dead workers from fleet state (Stopped, Error, Stale)
  migrate         Migrate the galaxy's memory — legacy flat→fleet, or residence-to-residence
  patrol          Patrol the fleet — health checks and anomaly detection
  health          Health — read-only molecule-health anomaly catalog, federation-wide (ADR-137 §7)
  pulse           Pulse — runtime-vitality reading: RPM tachometer, six-voyant strip (ADR-138 P1)
  project         Project — materialize views from the ledger (STATUS.md, ISSUES.md, GitHub Issues)
  reconcile       Reconcile — **deprecated** alias for `cs project` (ADR-052 §D3)
  scheduler       Scheduler — read-only view onto `cosmon-scheduler`'s state (patrols, last fires, log)
  session         Session — operator carnet (start/note/end), append-only, BLAKE3-sealed
  daemons         Daemons — operator view over `cosmon-daemon-supervisor` (list/status/reload/logs)
  status          Project pulse — quick DAG overview like git status
  tackle          Tackle a molecule — spawn ONE worker on this node (always leaf; for DAG walks use `cs run`)
  claim           Claim a molecule for the pilot; the runtime defers until it is released
  release         Release a pilot claim and return the molecule to the runtime frontier
  tag             Tag — add or remove typed labels on a molecule
  tail            Tail — live `notify`-driven reader over `events.jsonl` (fleet or `--all-galaxies`)
  paths           Paths — project the write-path taxonomy (`--writes`), a pure derived view
  done            Done — terminal teardown for a molecule (merge + cleanup, human-callable)
  harvest         Harvest — close a completed-but-unmerged molecule by invoking `cs done`
  stuck           Stuck — freeze a molecule and record the blocker
  await-operator  Await-operator — the only sanctioned way to block on an operator decision at an irreversibility boundary (ADR-123). Routes on the molecule's `op-block:*` capability: block-and-emit, or surface-and-continue
  topology        Topology — structural maps of the workspace (wraps the `topon` CLI)
  deps            Deps — show blocking dependencies for a molecule (upstream/downstream)
  diverge         Diverge — structural agreement check between two sessions on a molecule (turing §5)
  peek            Peek — canonical fleet observation command (TUI default; `--no-tui` for plaintext stream)
  wait            Wait — block until a molecule reaches a terminal (or requested) status
  run             Run — walk a molecule DAG of N≥1 nodes via the resident runtime (ADR-016 Layer B)
  spore           Spore germinates a whole polymer from a shareable `spore.toml` template (validate / run / export, ADR-140)
  help            Show help — all commands grouped, or detailed help for one command
  verify          Verify — walk a molecule's event hash chain (plumbing v2)
  validate        Validate — deliberate heavyweight project-milestone gate
  verify-trace    `verify-trace` — replay `events.jsonl` against the scheduler spec (Phase 3 CI gate)
  verify-graph    `verify-graph` — Tarjan SCC check on the subgraph induced by a typed relation (substrate, ADR-016)
  spec-audit      `spec-audit` — ledger audit against the TLA+ spec (catches c1cb `bypass_merge`)
  release-audit   `release-audit` — dry-run drift detector for the public distribution (analogue of `reconcile --check`)
  doctor          Doctor — diagnostic probes (whisper channel, …)
  demo            Demo — one-command end-to-end chatbot surface (first-contact experience)
  whisper         Whisper — inject a perturbation payload into a live worker's tmux pane (v0)
  archive         Archive — operator view over durable terminal snapshots (list/show/verify/prune, ADR-030)
  opt-in-share    Opt-in-share — first-run consent prompt for encrypted developer bundles
  notarize        Notarize — issue or verify an operator-signed attestation for a molecule (ADR-056)
  panel           Panel — convene a hash-pinned supermajority panel to gate a constitutional amendment
  witness         Witness — Layer-2 witness-quorum seal for stress-test molecules (ADR-085 §3)
  notify          Notify — push a one-line message to every configured operator channel
  key             Key — manage the operator's Ed25519 notary key (generate, show)
  config          Config — inspect `.cosmon/config.toml` (`show adapters`, `adapters`)

Options:
      --config <PATH>
          Path to configuration file

  -v, --verbose
          Enable verbose output

      --json
          Output in JSON format

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

  -V, --version
          Print version

REFERENCES:
  Operator handbook — run 'cs help guide' or read docs/handbook.md for conceptual clarification on cosmon's lifecycle, DAG, tags, and monitoring model.
  Help-text audit — an internal note records the per-command rationale for the examples rendered here.
